<h1>Alexis Haller</h1><p>&nbsp;Alexis Haller is a trial and appellate attorney with more than twenty-five years of experience in litigation, with a particular focus on the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act. He has obtained dismissals in numerous FSIA actions and has successfully represented a foreign head of state and foreign diplomatic agents. His practice spans criminal appeals, habeas proceedings, civil appeals, and international civil litigation, serving clients in California, across the United States, and overseas.</p><center><div class="separator" style="clear: both; text-align: center;"><img border="0" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEi-Npdip2x-BjGONNrcXClJae8DJcSuuJcN4V0znWeZANzvK3O6XWH4BOrWdS5Yb4zlJuy7lc9E9IQnlIhWCHKfppTzOwkb0KTvLOQeLlaveN2gGfjG34gupLO-DTfq7yDHj6o5knltQMa0dt5M3hUs1BVOBaoUoYclZfWwUjBtqi_0XjRIihuTczCqi1FN/s400/alexis%20%281%29.webp" /></div></center>
<p>&nbsp;Mr. Haller graduated summa cum laude from Princeton University in 1995 with a bachelor of arts degree in history, where he was a member of the Phi Beta Kappa Society and served as president of the American Whig-Cliosophic Society. He earned his juris doctor from Stanford Law School in 1998. Following law school, he joined the San Francisco boutique firm Swanson, McNamara & Haller LLP, where he worked from 1999 to 2009 as an associate and later as a name partner, handling a wide range of civil and criminal matters. In 2009, he established his own private practice, which he continues to lead as principal from Aptos, California.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Over the course of his career, Alexis Haller has litigated challenges to criminal indictments, motions to suppress evidence under the Fourth Amendment, and complex matters involving international law. His criminal practice includes representing clients accused of serious offenses such as murder, manslaughter, sexual assault and abuse, fraud, robbery, burglary, theft, and drug trafficking. In civil matters, he has handled appeals and international litigation involving personal injury torts, fraud, breach of contract, real property disputes, diplomatic immunity, and head-of-state immunity. While his international work often focuses on defending sovereign defendants, he also assists plaintiffsâ€™ attorneys seeking guidance in FSIA cases.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Mr. Haller has been licensed to practice law for over twenty-six years and is a member of the bars of California, Washington, and the District of Columbia. He is admitted to practice before the United States Supreme Court and the United States Courts of Appeals for the Second, Sixth, Seventh, and Ninth Circuits. He is also a member of the American Bar Association and the American Society of International Law. His law office is located at 7960B Soquel Drive, Suite 130, Aptos, California, where he practices litigation, international law, and criminal defense.</p>
<p>&nbsp;In addition to his litigation work, Mr. Haller has recently focused on the intersection of artificial intelligence and appellate practice. His work includes evaluating leading AI systems on complex federal criminal litigation, developing practical toolkits for appellate attorneys seeking to implement AI effectively, and convening the AI Appellate Group, a forum for California criminal defense appellate attorneys representing indigent clients to discuss real-world applications of AI in legal practice.</p>
<p>&nbsp;Alexis Haller is fluent in French, proficient in Italian, and has intermediate proficiency in Spanish. Outside of his professional life, he enjoys spending time with his family, reading, running, hiking, surfing, skiing, swimming, and following the New York Yankees.</p>
